---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import NavBar from "../../components/NavBar.astro";
import Footer from "../../components/Footer.astro";
---

<Layout
  title="Nominal vs Actual Lumber Sizes — Complete Reference"
  description="Why a 2x4 is not actually 2 by 4 inches. Reference table of common nominal lumber sizes and their actual dimensions."
>
  <NavBar />

  <main class="bg-primary">
    <article class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-8 py-16 sm:px-14 lg:px-24 lg:py-24">
      <div class="flex items-center gap-3 text-caption text-muted mb-2">
        <a href="/blog" class="text-accent-mustard no-underline hover:underline">Back to blog</a>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <time datetime="2026-06-03">June 3, 2026</time>
        <span>&middot;</span>
        <span>5 min read</span>
      </div>

      <h1 class="mt-4 text-display-xl text-primary">Nominal vs Actual Lumber Sizes</h1>
      <p class="mt-3 text-body-lg text-secondary leading-relaxed">
        Everything you need to know about why a 2x4 is 1.5 by 3.5 and how to avoid costly mistakes.
      </p>

      <div class="mt-10 space-y-6 text-body-md text-secondary leading-relaxed">

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-10">What Is the Difference?</h2>
        <p>
          The nominal size is what the lumber is called. The actual size is what it measures after it has been dried and planed smooth. When a tree is first cut into rough lumber at the sawmill, a 2&times;4 starts as a rough piece about 2 inches by 4 inches. Then it goes through a kiln to dry it, which causes shrinkage, and then through a planer to make the surfaces smooth and consistent. By the time it reaches the lumber rack, it is 1.5 inches by 3.5 inches.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is standard across the industry and has been for decades. It applies to all dimensional lumber sold in North America.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-10">Full Reference Table</h2>
        <div class="overflow-x-auto">
          <table class="w-full text-body-sm border-collapse">
            <thead>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle">
                <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 text-primary">Nominal</th>
                <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 text-primary">Actual (inches)</th>
                <th class="text-left py-2 pr-4 text-primary">Actual (mm)</th>
                <th class="text-left py-2 text-primary">Common Uses</th>
              </tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody class="text-secondary">
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;2</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 1.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 38</td><td class="py-2">Furring strips, small trim</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;3</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 2.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 64</td><td class="py-2">Battens, small cleats</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;4</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 3.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 89</td><td class="py-2">Shelving, trim, bracing</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;6</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 5.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 140</td><td class="py-2">Furniture, shelving</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;8</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 7.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 184</td><td class="py-2">Shelving, bench tops</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;10</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 9.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 235</td><td class="py-2">Wide shelving</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">1&times;12</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">0.75 &times; 11.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">19 &times; 286</td><td class="py-2">Wide shelves, benchtops</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;2</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 1.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 38</td><td class="py-2">Stakes, small supports</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;3</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 2.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 64</td><td class="py-2">Framing, blocking</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;4</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 3.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 89</td><td class="py-2">Wall framing, general</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;6</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 5.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 140</td><td class="py-2">Deck joists, headers</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;8</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 7.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 184</td><td class="py-2">Floor joists, beams</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;10</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 9.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 235</td><td class="py-2">Floor joists, rafters</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">2&times;12</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">1.5 &times; 11.25</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">38 &times; 286</td><td class="py-2">Headers, stair stringers</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">4&times;4</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">3.5 &times; 3.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">89 &times; 89</td><td class="py-2">Deck posts, columns</td></tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-subtle"><td class="py-2 pr-4">4&times;6</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">3.5 &times; 5.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">89 &times; 140</td><td class="py-2">Beams, heavy framing</td></tr>
              <tr><td class="py-2 pr-4">6&times;6</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">5.5 &times; 5.5</td><td class="py-2 pr-4">140 &times; 140</td><td class="py-2">Heavy posts, beams</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-10">Does This Apply to Hardwood Too?</h2>
        <p>
          Hardwood is sold differently. When you buy 4/4 (four-quarter) red oak, it is rough-sawn and measures about 1 inch thick. After planing, it might be 7/8 or 13/16 depending on how much you surface. The width is whatever the board happens to be, and you pay for the actual board feet based on the rough dimensions.
        </p>
        <p>
          Hardwood suppliers typically list thickness in quarters: 4/4 (1"), 5/4 (1.25"), 6/4 (1.5"), 8/4 (2"), etc. These are nominal rough thicknesses. The actual thickness after milling depends on how smooth you want the surface. This is different from construction lumber where the nominal and actual sizes are standardized.
        </p>

        <h2 class="text-display-sm text-primary mt-10">Why This Matters for Your Calculator</h2>
        <p>
          If you are entering dimensions into a board foot calculator and you use nominal sizes (2 &times; 4 instead of 1.5 &times; 3.5), your result will be off by roughly 25-30%. For a project using 100 board feet, that is a significant miscalculation. This calculator uses actual dimensions in its presets so you do not have to worry about it, but if you are entering custom sizes, make sure you are using the actual measurements.
        </p>

        <div class="mt-10 rounded-lg border border-subtle bg-secondary p-6">
          <p class="text-body-sm text-primary">
            <strong>Use actual dimensions:</strong> The <a href="/" class="text-accent-mustard underline decoration-accent-mustard/30 hover:decoration-accent-mustard">board foot calculator</a> on this site has Quick Fill presets with actual dimensions for common lumber sizes, so your calculations are always accurate.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </article>
  </main>

  <Footer />
</Layout>
